---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { FORUM_URL, withBase } from '../lib/site';
---

<Base
  title="Your Assistant"
  description="A local AI assistant that turns messy thoughts into concrete actions – running 100 % on your device. Setup, model guide, multiple assistants, teams and delegation, honestly explained."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Your Assistant</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      A local AI that turns messy thoughts into concrete actions: appointments, to-dos, notes,
      habits – proposed as cards, applied only when <em>you</em> say yes.
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="badge">● 100 % on your device</span>
    </p>
    <p class="muted hero__privacy">
      The assistant runs entirely on your machine. Your thoughts, your notes, your calendar –
      none of it ever leaves your device. The <strong>only</strong> network contact is the
      one-time model download from <code>huggingface.co</code>, and only when you click
      “Install”. After that, everything works offline. Forever.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card step">
    <h2>How it works: dump your thoughts, get cards back</h2>
    <p>
      You don't write commands. You write the way your head sounds. Say you type this into the
      assistant widget:
    </p>
    <div class="braindump">
      “dentist tomorrow 9am, buy milk, call Lisa back, want to read daily again”
    </div>
    <p>The assistant reads it, sorts it, and answers with proposal cards:</p>
    <div class="proposals">
      <div class="proposal">
        <span class="proposal__kind">📅 Appointment</span>
        <strong>Dentist</strong> – tomorrow, 9:00, with a reminder before it starts.
        <span class="proposal__actions"><b>Yes</b> · Edit · No</span>
      </div>
      <div class="proposal">
        <span class="proposal__kind">✓ To-do</span>
        <strong>Buy milk</strong>
        <span class="proposal__actions"><b>Yes</b> · Edit · No</span>
      </div>
      <div class="proposal">
        <span class="proposal__kind">✓ To-do</span>
        <strong>Call Lisa back</strong>
        <span class="proposal__actions"><b>Yes</b> · Edit · No</span>
      </div>
      <div class="proposal">
        <span class="proposal__kind">🔥 Habit</span>
        <strong>Read daily</strong> – added to your daily routine.
        <span class="proposal__actions"><b>Yes</b> · Edit · No</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      <strong>Nothing happens without your confirmation.</strong> Every card waits for
      <em>Yes</em>, <em>Edit</em> (fix the details first) or <em>No</em>. The assistant can only
      use the same commands you see in the command palette – it cannot invent actions, touch
      files behind your back, or delete anything silently.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      Trust it after a while? You can switch confirmation off per assistant in its settings –
      cards then apply immediately. Turning it back on is one click away, and it's on by default.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card step">
    <h2>Setup: three steps, no expertise needed</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Open <em>Settings → Assistant</em>.</strong> That's the whole entry point –
        the assistant is a built-in tool like any other, and its privacy light is green.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Let Cardo check your machine.</strong> The system check looks at your RAM and
        CPU cores (and recognizes Apple Silicon, which runs local models especially well). Every
        available model then gets an honest rating: <em>great</em>, <em>okay</em>, <em>slow</em>
        or <em>too big for this machine</em> – plus one clear recommendation. No guessing, no
        “it depends” – Cardo tells you what will actually feel good on <em>your</em> hardware.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>One click to install.</strong> Pick a model (the recommended one is a safe
        choice) and press install. This is the one moment Cardo contacts the internet: the model
        file is downloaded from <code>huggingface.co</code>, with a visible progress bar. Once
        it's done, you're offline-capable for good.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Right after that, the assistant asks a few <strong>personality questions</strong>: what
      it should be called, what it should call you, how it should talk (short &amp; direct,
      friendly, or detailed) and which language it should answer in. Two minutes, and it feels
      like yours.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card step">
    <h2>Choosing a model: an honest guide</h2>
    <p>
      Bigger models understand more nuance but need more RAM and answer more slowly. Smaller
      models are quick and light but occasionally miss subtleties. There is no “best” model –
      only the best one <em>for your machine and your patience</em>. Sizes below are rough
      values for the usual 4-bit builds Cardo installs; the system check gives you exact,
      per-machine ratings.
    </p>

