  <section class="card step">
    <h2>Personality, working style, memory: three plain files</h2>
    <p>
      Your assistant is not a black box. Everything that shapes it lives in three readable
      Markdown files on your disk – you can see (and edit) all of them under
      <em>Settings → Assistant → Advanced</em>:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><code>personality.md</code> – who it is.</strong> Its name, what it calls you,
        its tone (short &amp; direct / friendly / detailed) and its language. Generated from
        your answers to the personality questions; edit it any time.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><code>instructions.md</code> – how it works.</strong> The working rules: turn
        braindumps into concrete proposals, resolve “tomorrow” into a real date, never invent
        commands, when unsure propose anyway and let you fix it via <em>Edit</em>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><code>memory.md</code> – what it knows about you.</strong> Durable facts, one
        line each: preferences, recurring situations and how you like them solved, background
        that keeps coming up.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The memory follows two simple rules. First: <strong>the assistant checks its memory before
      asking you anything</strong> – if it already knows your dentist is Dr. Weber, it fills
      that in instead of asking again. Second: <strong>you always see what it remembers.</strong>
      Whenever it saves something new, a <em>“Remembered:”</em> line appears right in the
      conversation – and every entry has a <strong>✕ “forget this”</strong> next to it. One
      click, and it's gone from the file. No hidden profile, ever.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card step">
    <h2>Multiple assistants: one for each part of your life</h2>
    <p>
      You don't have to squeeze everything into one assistant. Create as many as you like, each
      with its own name, personality and job. A worked example:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Hanna</strong> – your work assistant. Tools: tasks and calendar only. Style:
        short &amp; direct. You dump your Monday chaos on her, she answers in bullet-length
        cards and never chats.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Felix</strong> – your writing companion. Tools: notes only. Style: warm and
        wordy. He helps you draft, rephrase and untangle texts, and never touches your calendar.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>They share one memory by default.</strong> That's deliberate: when you tell Hanna
      you're on vacation in August and later ask Felix to draft an out-of-office note, Felix
      already knows. Nothing gets lost just because you switched assistants. If you want a hard
      wall instead – say, a strict split between work and private life, where the work assistant
      must know <em>nothing</em> personal – you can give an assistant its own separate memory
      file in its settings. Shared is the default; separate is one switch.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tool scopes</strong> keep each assistant honest: Hanna literally cannot create a
      note, Felix cannot move an appointment – each one only sees the commands of the tools you
      gave it. <strong>Templates</strong> (work assistant, writing companion, planning helper …)
      give you a sensible starting point in one click, and you can
      <strong>export and import profiles</strong> as files – to move an assistant to your other
      machine, or to share a well-tuned one with a friend. Profiles contain the setup, not your
      memory, unless you explicitly include it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card step">
    <h2>Teams: several assistants, one conversation</h2>
    <p>
      Once you have a few assistants, you can group them into a <strong>team</strong> and talk
      to the team instead of picking who to ask. Behind the scenes a
      <strong>silent leader</strong> – always the fastest installed model, because its only job
      is routing – reads each question and hands it to the best-suited member. Silent means it
      never answers you itself; <strong>you always see who answered</strong>, right on the reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      Example – <em>Group 1: Hanna, Felix, Simon</em> (Simon being a research-minded assistant
      on a larger model):
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        “Move my Thursday 1-on-1 to Friday and remind me to prep” → the leader routes it to
        <strong>Hanna</strong> (calendar + tasks are her competence). Her cards appear, labeled
        <em>Hanna</em>.
      </li>
      <li>
        “Help me rewrite the intro of my blog post so it sounds less stiff” → routed to
        <strong>Felix</strong>. Warm, wordy, labeled <em>Felix</em>.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>When is a team worth it?</strong> If you have genuinely different jobs (planning
      vs. writing vs. thinking) that profit from different personalities or different model
      sizes, a team saves you the constant “who do I ask?”. If one assistant covers your day
      fine, stay with one – simpler is better here.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      The honest part about RAM: your machine can only hold so many models in memory at once.
      When the leader routes to a member whose model isn't currently loaded, Cardo swaps models
      – which means a short loading moment before that answer. Nothing is wrong; that's the
      price of running everything locally, and Cardo shows a loading state so you know what's
      happening.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card step">
    <h2>Delegation: assistants that know their limits</h2>
    <p>
      Even outside teams, assistants know about each other. Ask Hanna to polish a paragraph and
      she won't bluff – you get a card: <em>“Felix is better at this – hand it over?”</em> One
      click and Felix takes the request, with the same context; decline and Hanna does her best
      herself. Nothing is handed over without your confirmation, same as everything else.
    </p>
    <p>
      What drives this are <strong>competences</strong>: every assistant's profile lists what
      it's good at – derived from its tool scope, its model's strengths and its template. And
      competences are <strong>learned</strong>, too: when you accept a hand-over, that kind of
      request counts toward the receiving assistant's competences; when you decline, the system
      takes the hint. Over time, delegation suggestions match how <em>you</em> actually divide
      the work – you can view and edit each assistant's competence list in its settings at any
      time.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:1.25rem">
    <h2>FAQ</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>How much RAM do I really need?</summary>
      <p>
        The assistant starts at about 2–3 GB of free RAM for the smallest model (Qwen3 0.6B).
        A comfortable everyday setup is 8 GB total with a ~4B model; 16 GB opens up the 7–8B
        class; 12B+ models want 16–32 GB. The system check in <em>Settings → Assistant</em>
        rates every model against your actual machine before you download anything.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>How fast will it feel?</summary>
      <p>
        Local models answer in a visible stream, not instantly. Small models (≤2B) feel
        immediate; mid-size models (4–8B) take a few seconds for a typical braindump; large
        models take noticeably longer but understand more. Apple Silicon Macs are markedly
        faster than comparable x86 machines for this workload. If waiting annoys you, choose a
        smaller model – responsiveness matters more than the last bit of cleverness.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Which models are good at German (or other languages)?</summary>
      <p>
        Qwen3, Gemma 3 and Mistral are the strongest German speakers per size class, and handle
        many other languages well. Llama is solid but English-leaning, especially in the small
        3.2 models. Phi-4 and Granite are clearly English-first – fine for understanding German
        input, less polished when writing it. DeepSeek-R1 answers fine in German, but its
        visible “thinking” text often stays English.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>What about licenses?</summary>
      <p>
        Qwen3, Mistral and Granite are Apache-2.0; Phi-4 and DeepSeek-R1 are MIT – use freely.
        Llama models use Meta's community license, which requires a “Built with Llama” notice
        (Cardo displays it for you). Gemma models are under Google's Gemma Terms of Use; Cardo
        shows you those terms and asks for your consent before the download begins.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Why does it load for a few seconds when I switch assistants?</summary>
      <p>
        If the assistant you switch to uses a different model than the one currently in memory,
        Cardo has to unload one and load the other from disk. That's the short loading moment –
        it's normal, it's local, and it's the trade-off for being able to run several models on
        one machine. Assistants sharing the same model switch instantly.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Is anything sent to a server?</summary>
      <p>
        No. Your prompts, files, memory and answers never leave your device – the model runs
        inside Cardo, not in a cloud. The single exception is the model download itself: when
        you click install, the model file is fetched from <code>huggingface.co</code>. That
        request transfers the file to you; it does not carry your data anywhere.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Can I use it offline?</summary>
      <p>
        Yes – completely, once a model is downloaded. Plane, dead zone, deliberately offline
        machine: the assistant keeps working exactly the same. It never needs to phone home,
        because there is no home to phone.
      </p>
    </details>

    <p style="margin-top:1rem">
      More questions? The <a href={withBase('/docs')}>docs</a> cover the rest of Cardo, and the
      <a href={FORUM_URL} rel="noopener">forum</a> is open for everything else. Don't have Cardo
      yet? It's on the <a href={withBase('/download')}>download page</a> – free, no account.
    </p>
  </section>

  <style>
